---
globs: src/domain/entities/**/*.entity.ts
alwaysApply: false
---
Create domain entities following these rules:

Entities must be implemented as classes.
All properties must be defined in the constructor.
Entities must include a static fromObject method.

The fromObject method must:

Receive a plain object as parameter
Extract properties using destructuring
Support both id and _id fields
Validate required fields
Throw domain errors when validation fails
Return a new instance of the entity

Use strict typing and avoid any when possible.
Optional properties must be defined using ?.
Use readonly properties when possible to avoid mutations.

Entities must:

Be framework agnostic
Not depend on infrastructure
Contain only validation logic
Be simple and readable

Use the following format as reference:

export class CategoryEntity{

    constructor(
        public id: String,
        public name: String,
        public description: String,
        public slug: String,
        public lastPost?: PostEntity,
        public totalPosts?: number
    ){}

    static fromObject = (object: {[key: string]: any}) => {
        const { id, _id, name, description, slug, lastPost, totalPosts = 0} = object;

        if(!id || !_id) {
            CustomError.badRequest("Category id missing");
        }

        if(!name){
            CustomError.badRequest("Category name invalid");
        }

        if(!description){
            CustomError.badRequest("Category description invalid");
        }

        if(!slug){
            CustomError.badRequest("Category slug invalid");
        }

        return new CategoryEntity(id || _id, name, description, slug, lastPost, totalPosts);
    }
}